[0.005, "o", "\u001b[1;3HDevelopment Value: \"GP\"\u001b[35X\u001b[2;3HProduction Value: \"GP\"\u001b[20X\u001b[3;3Hhttps://php.net/request-order\u001b[15X\r\nrequest_order =\u001b[92m \"GP\"\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[30X\r\n\u001b[49X\u001b[6;3HThis directive determines whether PHP registers $argv & $argc each time it\u001b[7;2H runs. $argv contains an array of all the arguments passed to PHP when a script\r\n; is invoked. $argc contains an integer representing the number of arguments\u001b[9;3Hthat were passed when the script was invoked. These arrays are extremely\u001b[10;3Huseful when running scripts from the command line. When this directive is\u001b[11;3Henabled, registering these variables consumes CPU cycles and memory each time\u001b[12;3Ha script is executed. For security reasons, this feature should be disabled\u001b[13;3Hfor non-CLI SAPIs.    \u001b[14;3HNote: This directive is ignored for the CLI SAPI\u001b[15;2H This directive is deprecated.\u001b[6X\r\n; https://php.net/register-argc-argv\u001b[17;2Hregister_argc_argv = Off\u001b[22X\r\n\u001b[18X\u001b[19;3HWhen enabled, the ENV, REQUEST and SERVER variables are created when they're\u001b[20;3Hfirst used (Just In Time) instead of when the script starts. If these\u001b[21;3Hvariables are not used within a script, having this directive on will result\u001b[22;2H in a performance gain. The PHP directive register_argc_argv must be disabled\r\n; for this directive to have any effect.\u001b[24;3Hhttps://php.net/auto-globals-jit\u001b[41X\r\nauto_globals_jit =\u001b[92m On\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[15X\r\n\u001b[24X\n; Whether PHP will read the POST data.\r\n; This option is enabled by default.\u001b[29;3HMost likely, you won't want to disable this option globally. It causes $_POST\u001b[30;3Hand $_FILES to always be empty; the only way you will be able to read the\u001b[31;3HPOST data will be through the php://input stream wrapper. This can be useful\u001b[32;3Hto proxy requests or to process the POST data in a memory efficient fashion.\u001b[33;3Hhttps://php.net/enable-\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpost\u001b[m\u000f-data-reading\u001b[25X\u001b[34;2Henable_\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpost\u001b[m\u000f_data_reading = Off\u001b[69X\r\n\u001b[18X\u001b[36;3HMaximum size of POST data that PHP will accept.\u001b[37;3HIts value may be 0 to disable the limit. It is ignored if POST data reading\u001b[38;3His disabled through enable_\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpost\u001b[m\u000f_data_reading.\r\n; https://php.net/\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpost\u001b[m\u000f-max-size\r\n\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpost\u001b[m\u000f_max_size =\u001b[92m 8M\u001b[m\u000f\r\n\u001b[5X\u001b[42;3HAutomatically add files before PHP document.\u001b[29X\u001b[43;19Hauto-prepend-file\r\nauto_prepend_file =\u001b[46;3HAutomatically add files after PHP document.\u001b[47;19Hauto-append-file\r\nauto_append_file =    \u001b[50;3HBy default, PHP will output a media type using the Content-Type header. To\u001b[51;3Hdisable this, simply set it to be empty.\u001b[52;2H\u001b[31X\r\n; PHP's built-in default media type is set to text/html.\u001b[54;3Hhttps://php.net/default-mimetyp\r\ndefault_mimetype =\u001b[92m \"text/html\"\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[18X\r\n\u001b[39X\n; PHP's default character set is set to UTF-8.\u001b[58;3Hhttps://php.net/default-charset\u001b[18X\r\ndefault_charset =\u001b[92m \"UTF-8\"\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[17X\r\n\u001b[32X\n; PHP internal character encoding is set to empty.\u001b[62;3HIf empty, default_charset is used.\u001b[54X\u001b[63;3Hhttps://php.net/internal-encoding\u001b[64;2Hinternal_encoding =\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f686,26         36\u001b[67;6H\u001b[?25h"]
